Description

A drinking water dispenser with two taps but without any labels indicating which tap provides hot water and which provides cold water, making it difficult for users to identify the correct tap.

Source of Photography

Captured Photograph

Place

VIT University, Vellore – Drinking Water Station

Reasons Why This Design is Bad

The taps are not labeled, causing confusion for users.

Users may accidentally dispense hot water instead of cold water, leading to a risk of burns.

First-time visitors cannot easily identify the purpose of each tap.

Reduces usability and increases the chance of user errors.

The absence of clear visual guidance makes the dispenser less user-friendly.
Suggested Improvement

Add clear "Hot Water" and "Cold Water" labels above each tap using distinct colors (red for hot and blue for cold).

Use durable, waterproof stickers or engraved labels for long-term visibility.

Include warning symbols or a "Caution: Hot Water" sign near the hot water tap to prevent accidental burns.

Add Braille or tactile markings to improve accessibility for visually impaired users.

Use color-coded tap handles to make identification even easier.
